The '''Kenya sparrow''' ('''''Passer rufocinctus'''''), also known as the '''Kenya rufous sparrow''', is a [[Old World sparrow|sparrow]] found in Kenya and Tanzania. It tends to be found in dry wooded [[savannah]] and agricultural areas.<ref>{{harvnb|Summers-Smith|1988|pp=86–87}}</ref><ref name=BirdLife/> Some authorities have lumped the [[great sparrow]] (''P.&nbsp;motitensis''), the Kenya sparrow, and the [[Socotra sparrow]] (''P.&nbsp;insularis'') into ''P.&nbsp;motitensis'' following Dowsett and Forbes-Watson (1993).<ref name=BirdLife>{{cite web|author=BirdLife International|author-link=BirdLife International|year=2010|url=http://www.birdlife.org/datazone/species/index.html?action=SpcHTMDetails.asp&sid=8375&m=0|title=Species factsheet: ''Passer rufocinctus''|access-date=24 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Dowsett|Forbes-Watson|1993}}</ref> Some authorities also lump [[Shelley's sparrow]] and the [[Kordofan sparrow]] with this species, or all three with the great sparrow.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Kirwan|first=Guy M.|year=2008|title=Studies of Socotran Birds III. Morphological and mensural evidence for a 'new' species in the Rufous Sparrow ''Passer motitensis'' complex endemic to the island of Abd 'Al Kuri, with the validation of ''Passer insularis'' Sclater & Hartlaub, 1881|journal=[[Bulletin of the British Ornithologists' Club]]|volume=128|issue=2|pages=83–93}}</ref>

